          "body": "Verse 3 identifies the chapter's one safe category: the anav, the humble of the earth who have already been carrying out His ordinances. These are not passive bystanders; their humility is proved by prior obedience to mishpat (justice, right order). The promise offered — 'perhaps you will be hidden' (satar) — is deliberately restrained. Zephaniah does not promise absolute immunity from all suffering; he promises the possibility of divine concealment on the Day of God's wrath, which is the most any creature can ask. The remnant reappears in verses 7 and 9, now inheriting what the condemned nations lost. Philistia's coast becomes their pastureland (2:7); Moab's territory becomes their plunder (2:9). This is the canonical pattern of the Psalms (37:9, 11 — the meek shall inherit the earth) refracted through prophetic judgment: the low are raised precisely because the high are brought down. Peter Davids, commenting on James 1:9-11, identifies the same eschatological reversal at work in the wisdom tradition."
