          "title": "Cush and Assyria — south and north, no exceptions",
          "body": "The southern oracle is a single verse (2:12): 'You also, O Ethiopians, will be slain by My sword.' Its brevity is deliberate. The great Nubian empire that had recently dominated Egypt receives one line — not because it is less important geographically, but because the point has been made by accumulation. The northern oracle (2:13-15) is the chapter's climax. Assyria was the world-empire, Nineveh its showcase capital. Zephaniah pictures it as a desert haunted by desert owls and hedgehogs roosting on its column capitals, birds singing in windows where human voices once argued politics, desolation lying on the threshold of the throne room. The cedar paneling — expensive imported luxury — is exposed and stripped. Every marker of imperial grandeur is inverted. And verse 15 provides the theological caption: 'This is the exultant city that said in her heart, I am, and there is no one besides me.' The phrase 'I am, and there is no one besides me' is verbatim God's own self-description in Isaiah 45:5-6 and 46:9. Nineveh had stolen the language of deity. The punishment is therefore not merely political — it is theological correction, the restoration of the divine exclusive."
