          "body": "Read as a whole, Zephaniah 2 moves from the specific to the universal and from the conditional to the certain. It begins with an appeal that has a condition (seek before the Day) and a specific remnant (humble Judah). It ends with an archetype (Nineveh's boast and fall) that applies to every nation in every era. The four-directional oracle structure encloses Judah in a ring of judged nations, making the point that the LORD's jurisdiction is total. But the ring is not just a cage — it is evidence. The same power that dismantles Philistia, Moab, Ammon, Cush, and Assyria is the power being offered as shelter to the humble in verse 3. Calvin, in his commentary on Zephaniah, observes that the foreign oracles serve the church precisely by demonstrating that 'there is no corner of the world to which God's judgment does not penetrate.' The chapter's pastoral logic is therefore: if you have seen what He does to the proud, you know what shelter from His anger is worth. Seek it while the window is open."
